The paper deals with the problem of distributed parallelism for feature tracking and visualization, which involves handling large amounts of scientific data. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. Additionally, the paper specifically mentions tracking critical points on exploding wire experimental data and tracking super level sets on BOUT++ fusion plasma simulations, which are both related to computer vision (cs.CV) and graphics (cs.GR). The paper also involves constructing and partitioning a high-dimensional mesh, which could fall under the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) category. Finally, the paper deals with deriving insights from scientific data, which could fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category.
